### Objects in C#

An object is an instance of a class. It represents a concrete entity with state and behavior.

### Creating Objects

```csharp
ClassName objectName = new ClassName();
// or with var
var objectName = new ClassName();
// or with target-typed new (C# 9+)
ClassName objectName = new();
```

### Object Initialization

```csharp
// Default constructor
Person person1 = new Person();
person1.Name = "Alice";
person1.Age = 30;

// Object initializer (C# 3+)
Person person2 = new Person
{
    Name = "Bob",
    Age = 25
};

// Constructor with parameters
Person person3 = new Person("Charlie", 35);
```

### Object Members

```csharp
var car = new Car();
car.Make = "Honda";        // Set property
string model = car.Model;  // Get property
car.Start();               // Call method
```

### Reference Type Behavior

Objects are reference types - variables hold references, not the actual data:

```csharp
Person p1 = new Person { Name = "Alice" };
Person p2 = p1;  // Both reference the same object
p2.Name = "Bob";
Console.WriteLine(p1.Name);  // "Bob"
```

### Object Equality

```csharp
Person a = new Person { Name = "Alice" };
Person b = new Person { Name = "Alice" };

Console.WriteLine(a == b);          // False (different references)
Console.WriteLine(a.Equals(b));     // False (unless overridden)
Console.WriteLine(ReferenceEquals(a, b));  // False
```

### Anonymous Objects

```csharp
var person = new { Name = "Dave", Age = 40 };
Console.WriteLine($"{person.Name}, {person.Age}");
```

### Object Lifecycle

| Stage | Description |
|-------|-------------|
| Declaration | Variable declaration |
| Instantiation | Memory allocation with `new` |
| Initialization | Setting initial state |
| Usage | Accessing members |
| Garbage Collection | Automatic memory cleanup |

> **Key Point:** Use object initializers for concise object creation. Remember that objects are reference types - assignment creates another reference, not a copy. Compare objects by value using `.Equals()` (if overridden) rather than `==` (which checks reference equality by default).

### Object Casting

```csharp
object obj = new Person();
Person p = (Person)obj;  // Explicit cast
Person? p2 = obj as Person;  // Safe cast
bool isPerson = obj is Person;  // Type check
```

codeExample:
using System;

public class Book
{
    public string Title { get; set; }
    public string Author { get; set; }
    public int Pages { get; set; }

    public void DisplayInfo()
    {
        Console.WriteLine($"'{Title}' by {Author} ({Pages} pages)");
    }
}

class Program
{
    static void Main()
    {
        // Object initializer
        var book = new Book
        {
            Title = "1984",
            Author = "George Orwell",
            Pages = 328
        };

        book.DisplayInfo();
    }
}
